<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Care for AIDS Orphans: Agency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The United States Agency for
International Development (USAID) Thursday called on the world to
treat children orphaned by the AIDS pandemic with greater love and
compassion.
</P>
<P>
"The world community must unite in compassionate response and
support," the government aid group said in its "Children on the
Brink" report released on Thursday at the 13th International AIDS
Conference in Durban, South Africa.
</P>
<P>
"We must scale up responses dramatically. The HIV/AIDS
pandemic is producing orphans on a scale unrivaled in world
history," said John Williamson, co-author of the report.
</P>
<P>
Revised estimates said that 15.6 million children under the age
of 15 have already lost their mother or both parents to AIDS or
other causes.
</P>
<P>
According to USAID, AIDS will produce 24.3 million orphans by
2010 even by conservative estimates.
</P>
<P>
The disease's soaring infection rates would continue for at
least another three decades and if infection rates continue at the
current pace, the figure is likely to be 44 million and 88 percent
of them will live in sub-Saharan Africa, USAID said.
</P>
<P>
The disease is killing breadwinners and communities are being
wiped out, the organization said, noting that children are going
without food, education, role models and other basic rights like
the need for affection and care.
</P>
<P>
In its study covering 34 developing countries, USAID said that
AIDS currently accounts for about half of all orphans and this
figure are expected to surge.
</P>
<P>
The orphan crisis is holistic and all parentless children
require care, not only those with HIV, USAID stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
