<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNICEF Hails Nigeria's Women Empowerment Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Children's Fund (
UNICEF) has commended Nigeria's efforts in improving the lot of
the country's women by making and implementing sound national
policies on women.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a conference on "Gender equality, development and
peace for the 21st century" in the Nigerian capital Abuja on
Wednesday, the agency's representative in Nigeria Georgiana Ngeri-
Nwagha said that Nigeria is on the path to full women empowerment.
</P>
<P>
She described the ban on female genital mutilation in Edo,
Cross River and Ogun states in southern Nigeria as "one of the
most courageous decisions" and hoped that other states would
follow suit, the News Agency of Nigeria reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Ngeri-Nwagha welcomed the inclusion of six female ministers in
the current cabinet of the Nigerian government and praised the new
national policy on women and an improved female enrollment in
schools.
</P>
<P>
However, she complained about the continued existence of the
practice of early marriages, wife battering and discrimination
against girls, as well as the problems of AIDS and a high
mortality rate among women as areas that require serious attention
to ensure true emancipation of women.
</P>
<P>
She pledged the agency's continued assistance to women
development programs in the west African country.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's first lady Stella Obasanjo told the conference that
since women form 50 percent of the productive capacity, failure to
harness their potentials would affect the growth of any economy.
</P>
<P>
Realization has transformed the equality question from its
former social, legal and moral aspects to an economic imperative,
which has won more men over to the positive side of the gender
equality debate, she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
