<HEADLINE> Death Toll of Nigeria Pipeline Fire Rises to 300 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The death toll from Monday night's
oil pipeline explosion at villages near Nigeria's oil town Warri
in the country's southern Niger Delta region has risen to 300.
</P>
<P>
Information Minister Jerry Gana, who confirmed the death toll
in the capital Abuja on Thursday, expressed the government's
condolence to the families of the victims and said that relevant
agents had been dispatched to the scene for on-the-spot assessment.
</P>
<P>
"Please help to educate our people that they can do better
things with their hands instead of risking their lives," the
minister said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Delta Governor James Ibori, who described the
accident as an "avoidable holocaust", urged the federal government
to institute a commission of inquiry into the incident.
</P>
<P>
The governor has set up his own task force to prevent a
recurrence of such accidents, which took place from time to time.
</P>
<P>
Authorities of the state had earlier appealed for the wounded
to come forward for hospital treatment.
</P>
<P>
Most of the injured have reportedly sought help from
traditional doctors because they feared arrest on suspicion of
stealing oil if they had gone to hospitals.
</P>
<P>
The explosion occurred between the villages of Adeje and Ovire
Court outside Warri, a major oil town in the south of Africa's
largest oil-exporting country, when people were using buckets to
collect petrol flowing from the pipeline after it had been
punctured by thieves on Sunday night. 
</P>
</TEXT>
