<HEADLINE> Kenya to Boost Handling of Transit Cargo: President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi
Friday said that his government has embarked on restructuring
measures aimed at expediting handling of transit cargo by
improving effectiveness and efficiency of the Port of Mombasa in
southeastern Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Moi made the remarks here when holding lengthy talks with
visiting Rwandese President Paul Kagame, who arrived in the
country Friday morning for a two-day visit.
</P>
<P>
Since a sizable volume of Rwanda's imports and exports transit
through Kenya, Moi said, his government is undergoing
rehabilitation of the northern corridor and has introduced block
trains by the State Railway Corporation to facilitate quick
passage of transit cargo.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Moi told his counterpart that the prospects
of the establishment of a free trade area among the members of the
Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa will create new
opportunities for boosting trade between Kenya and Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
Moi expressed his hope that President Kagame's visit will
enable the two countries to enhance bilateral cooperation in
various fields such transport and communications, commerce, human
resources, agriculture and judiciary.
</P>
<P>
Kagame said he is looking forward to the acceptance of Rwanda
in the East African Community, for which his country had already
applied.
</P>
<P>
The Rwandese President said that his delegation includes
businessmen from Rwanda who are here to learn from Kenyans.
</P>
<P>
This is Kagame's second visit to Kenya in two months since he
became the head of state in April this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
