<HEADLINE> Tanzanian President Says No Compromise to Please Donors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania will never
compromise its independence and national dignity to please some
donors or creditors, President Benjamin Mkapa told the parliament
in the central town of Dodoma on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Much as we badly need foreign financial aid and loans, we are
not prepared to let our independence and national dignity be the
price for aid and loans," the president said in a farewell address
to the House.
</P>
<P>
The National Assembly, the parliament of Tanzania, is to be
dissolved in August to pave the way for the general elections to
be held on October 29.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, however, Mkapa thanked various donors and
creditors for supporting the country's economic and social
development programs, including the World Bank and the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) for giving the country hefty
debt reliefs.
</P>
<P>
The government has in the last five years won the confidence of
many donors and creditors without compromising the country's
independence and national dignity, he said.
</P>
<P>
He warned of the emerging habit of some political parties to go
abroad in search of financial aid or send complaints to donor
countries on issues that could be solved domestically.
</P>
<P>
According to Mkapa, his government needs foreign support to
ensure the freedom and fairness in the forthcoming general
elections, but not assistance aimed at strengthening a particular
political party or destroying any party.
</P>
<P>
"We are welcoming election observers, but not supervisors and
tutors of democracy," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We are a free nation. Nobody outside Tanzania gave us the
right to vote. We secured the right ourselves after struggling for
the independence of Tanganyika and the gallant Zanzibar Revolution,
" he said.
</P>
<P>
The president noted that despite various difficulties,
including drought and floods, Tanzania's economy is doing well and
registering impressive growth.
</P>
<P>
The economy grew at more than 4 percent, while inflation was
brought down to 6.6 percent as of May this year from around 30
percent in 1995, he said.
</P>
<P>
The coming elections will be Tanzania's second multi-party
election. Mkapa is seeking reelection for a second five-year term.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
