<HEADLINE> Mandela Calls for Urgent Steps to Save Children from AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Former South African
President Nelson Mandela Friday called for urgent steps to protect
the country's children from the HIV/AIDS scourge.
</P>
<P>
He was speaking while receiving a 35-million-rand (about 5
million U.S. dollars) grant from the United States Agency for
International Development (USAID) to support AIDS orphans in South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
Unless the spread of HIV/AIDS is curbed, the epidemic would be
worsened, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Mandela, children seem to bear the brunt of nature
's anger and men's misfortunes. "No one can dispute the need for
us to respond to those who need help most," he said.
</P>
<P>
The number of orphans in South Africa is currently estimated to
be between 500,000 and 800,000 and by 2005 the figure could be as
high as 1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
No government, not even the South African government, could
fight the disease by itself, Mandela said, stressing that "it
needs a concerted effort."
</P>
<P>
Mandela urged the South African government to take bold
initiatives to prevent new infections among young people and to
initiate large-scale action to prevent mother-to-child
transmission.
</P>
<P>
The USAID grant is aimed to cater for programs to address the
socio-economic needs of orphans and vulnerable children affected
and infected by HIV/AIDS. 
</P>
</TEXT>
