<HEADLINE> Afghan Ex-King's Envoys to Talk with Pakistani Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 14 (Xinhua) -- A high level delegation of
former Afghan king Zahir Shah is scheduled to be here on Monday
for talks with Pakistani officials over the "Loya Jirga" (Grand
Assembly) proposal, a peace initiative for ending the protracted
Afghan conflict.
</P>
<P>
Hedayat Amin Arsala, former Afghan foreign minister, who will
lead the delegation, has already arrived in Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
Arsala told reporters here on his arrival Friday that the
delegation plans to meet Pakistani officials to explain the Loya
Jirga approach.
</P>
<P>
"We plan to explain the Jirga process as a means of promoting
peace process in the war-shattered Afghanistan to seek Pakistan's
support," he said.
</P>
<P>
Former autocrat Zahir Shah, who is on exile, has recently
proposed to hold a Loya Jirga, namely an assembly of
representatives from all Afghan factions, to find a peaceful
solution to the long-running civil war in the country.
</P>
<P>
Arsala said a delegation will also be sent to Afghanistan for
talks with the ruling Taliban militia and the northern opposition
alliance United Front. "We hope that the delegation will be able
to convince both sides about the need for peace and the wisdom of
the Jirga approach."
</P>
<P>
He said they hope the Jirga to be held inside Afghanistan. "
However, where exactly the Jirga will be held depends on our
discussions with the Taliban and the United Front. What is
important is, however, that the Loya Jirga is absolutely free and
is not under the control of any of the warring sides," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
