<HEADLINE> Ex-Ruling Party Challenges Verdict of Coup in Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Pakistan Muslim League (PML),
the former ruling party, Friday filed a review petition in the
Supreme Court, challenging the court's May 12 judgment which
legitimized the military takeover last year.
</P>
<P>
The petition was filed by Bilahi Buksh Soomro, the speaker of
the suspended National Assembly, Raja Zafar ul Haq, number two in
PML second to jailed ex-premier Nawaz Sharif, and Chaudhry Pervez
Elahi, speaker of the suspended assembly of Punjab province,
sources from the Supreme Court said here.
</P>
<P>
The petition argued that the Supreme Court verdict was contrary
to the spirit of the constitution and validation of the military
takeover was not correct.
</P>
<P>
On May 12, an 11-member bench of the apex court judged
unanimously that the military coup on October 12, 1999, which led
to the dismissal of Sharif's government, was valid because it was
an act of necessity. The court also empowered Chief Executive
General Pervez Musharraf to amend the consitution.
</P>
<P>
The 18-page review petition said the doctrine of necessity
could be used as a basis for "derailing democracy."
</P>
<P>
It also opposed the Supreme Court observation of giving the
right of amendment in the constitution to General Musharraf,
saying that the court itself does not have the right of amending
the constitution and therefore it could not delegate the power to
the military government.
</P>
<P>
Wasim Sajjad, chairman of suspended Senate, will be the PML
counsel in the hearing about the petition while former minister of
law Khalid Anwar will assist him. 
</P>
</TEXT>
