<HEADLINE> Angola Detects Over 30 Illegal Fishing Boats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Angola, through a newly installed
Sea Satellite Control System, has in the past six months recorded
31 violations by industrial fishing boats poaching into its waters,
the official news agency Angop reported here on Friday .
</P>
<P>
The Angolan Ministry of Fisheries was quoted as saying that the
violators, including both foreign and local ship operators, have
been charged.
</P>
<P>
The new system allowed the localization of ships' position,
speed and directions, through the "blue box" installed aboard the
ships. So far, the concerned department in charge of the combat
against illegal fishing activities has installed the satellite
control system in 54 fishing boats and other boats will be fitted
soon.
</P>
<P>
Angola is one of the major fish producers in Africa, with the
output at some 202,000 tons in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The country has fishing cooperation agreements with the
European Union, Russia and some Asian countries, but illegal
fishing activities has affected its fish production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
