<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IAS Calls International AIDS Conference Success </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"In Durban we had the chance to increase our knowledge
regarding the way to contrast HIV/AIDS by listening to a series of
excellent contributions coming from the western and eastern world,
and to share awareness and best practice from the North and South,
" said IAS outgoing president Mark Wainberg.
</P>
<P>
New IAS president Stefano Vella agreed. "Staying here in Africa
we were able to catch the world's attention towards the AIDS
pandemic, that could reach the dimension of a real catastrophe in
other continents as well," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the conference had focused more on the social and
behavioral impact of AIDS than on scientific research, but the
level of science presented is still "cutting-edge".
</P>
<P>
Both Vella and Wainberg agreed that the historic Durban
conference had run "smoothly in a safe and warm atmosphere".
</P>
<P>
More than 10,000 delegates took home the message from the 13th
AIDS conference that there was proof that the use of a combination
of anti-retroviral drugs to fight HIV had been successful.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Wainberg said IAS is committed itself to holding
future international AIDS conferences in poorer countries, but the
developing world will have to wait until the 2006 host is
announced.
</P>
<P>
The 2002 meeting will be held in Barcelona, Spain and the 2004
conference in Toronto, Canada.
</P>
<P>
However, Vella said he was angry with colleagues who did not
attend the conference because of perceived security threats and
the distance, noting that some scientists apparently opted not to
attend the event because they thought it would not be scientific
enough.
</P>
<P>
The cost of the 13th International AIDS Conference was
reportedly 60 million rand (8.8 million U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
