<HEADLINE> Number of Ethiopians in Need of Relief Food Reaches 10.5 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The number of people facing
food shortage in Ethiopia has increased to 10.5 million, the
country's Disaster Prevention and Preparedness Commission said on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
This number was based on the findings of the various study
teams dispatched to assess the drought conditions in all regions
except states of Somali and Afar, according to a statement by the
commission.
</P>
<P>
Officials with the commission said that signs of another round
of drought are beginning to emerge in Jimma zone, Oromia State and
the government has extended new appeal to major international
organizations for another 495,000 tons in food aid.
</P>
<P>
According to the officials, 400,000 tons of grain out of the
previously pledged 784,000 tons has reached the country.
</P>
<P>
However, the available stock amounting to 83,000 tons is too
inadequate for meeting the emergency needs, they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
