<HEADLINE> Egypt's Consultative Council Amends 1956 Election Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's Shura (Consultative) Council
on Saturday approved amendments to the election law passed in 1956
in a bid to ensure the parliamentary elections to be monitored by
judges.
</P>
<P>
The council, under speaker Mustafa Kamal Helmi, unanimously
endorsed the amendments according to a republican decree issued by
President Hosni Mubarak on Wednesday, Egypt's official Middle East
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The council does not have legislative powers and only issues
policy recommendations.
</P>
<P>
The modifications came following a ruling by the Supreme
Constitutional Court a week ago that the 1956 law was
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
Under Egypt's constitution, all the polling stations for
parliamentary elections should be supervised by members of the
judiciary. But the 1956 law allows civil servants to oversee
smaller booths while demanding the principal stations be monitored
by members of the judiciary.
</P>
<P>
The country's opposition parties have long been charging that
the government has relentlessly rigged parliamentary elections and
calling for changes.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak called on Wednesday for emergency meetings of the Shura
Council and the People's Assembly (parliament) to introduce the
modifications to the 1956 law.
</P>
<P>
The assembly is due to take a similar decision on Sunday after
its Legislative and Constitutional Committee endorsed the
amendments on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is expected to hold parliamentary elections in November.
Its last elections were in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
