economic cooperation to alleviate the impact of the decade-old
international sanctions on Iraq, Jordan's official news agency
Petra reported.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Ramadan reviewed the situation in Iraq under
the embargo imposed on Iraq since its 1990 invasion of Kuwait, and
voiced appreciation for Jordan's support for Iraq during the years
of embargo, Petra said without elaborating.
</P>
<P>
King Abdullah and Jordanian officials have used all possible
occasions to call for an end to the internationals sanctions on
Iraq, which Baghdad said had resulted in the deaths of over 1.5
million people, most of whom were children and the elderly.
</P>
<P>
Ramadan arrived in Amman Friday evening on a two day visit at a
time when officials from the two countries are eyeing for closer
economic cooperation and hoping to increase bilateral trade volume
to 800 million U.S. dollars from the current 300 million dollars
each year.
</P>
<P>
Jordan managed to keep its traditional friendly ties with Iraq
though it had taken drastic measures to improve its relations with
Kuwait and Saudi Arabia, Iraq's main Arab foes.
</P>
<P>
Currently Iraq is the only oil and oil product supplier to
Jordan, providing 50,000 to 75,000 barrels of crude oil a day to
Amman at discounted prices, or less than half of the current price
on international markets.
</P>
<P>
The kingdom sided with Iraq during the Gulf crisis that was
sparked by Iraq's invasion of Kuwait and had been isolated by Gulf
states, particularly Kuwait and Saudi Arabia.  
