<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 15 (Xinhua) -- An average of some 1,000
refugees from the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) continue
to enter Tanzania's western Kigoma region each month in a bid to
flee fierce fighting between the rebel and government forces.
</P>
<P>
Marion Roche, head of the United Nations High Commissioner for
Refugees (UNHCR) sub-office in Kigoma, said on Saturday that the
flow of refugees from the DRC has been pretty much the same since
the end of last year despite the pullout of Rwandan and Ugandan
troops from the northeastern DRC city of Kisangani.
</P>
<P>
"Most of the refugees who enter Kigoma still talk of fighting
in Congo," she said.
</P>
<P>
The official quoted refugees from Kisangani as saying that
stray bullets regularly fall over the town, with thousands of
rockets flying in all directions.
</P>
<P>
But the flow of Burundi refugees into Tanzania is generally in
decline although the cause can not be immediately explained, she
said.
</P>
<P>
She said that "refugees from Burundi say there is still
fighting in some parts of the country, and most of the refugees we
get are from border towns."
</P>
<P>
According to latest statistics issued by the Tanzanian
government, the country is currently sheltering around 664,000
refugees fleeing from Burundi, the DRC, Rwanda and Somalia due to
unstable situations in these countries. 
</P>
