said the number of telephone lines in the country will rise to
about 400,000 by the end of this year, expressing his hope that
this number will reach 1 million at the end of 2005.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- An economic study issued by the general federation of
Egypt's chamber of commerce revealed the genuine reasons for the
decline in Egypt's exports despite their relative advantages.
</P>
<P>
The reasons included the government restrictions on exports, the
focusing on domestic market, a protectionist policy that led to
neglecting the improvement of exports quality and the state control
on the productive sector.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The Guney Ege Gucbirligi Holding, a Turkish company
based in Soke, a town in the country's southwest Aydin province,
signed on Saturday a cooperation agreement with the British
National Wind Power company to produce electricity from wind
energy.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the signing ceremony, Soke Mayor Belig Azbazdar said
that the Guney Ege Gucbirligi Holding is making its first
investment in energy and that the wind energy potential in the
region is high.
</P>
<P>
David Butter Wort, president of the International Projects
Department of the British National Wind Power company, noted that
Turkey has a significant wind energy potential and that they
believe that electricity production from wind will be widened in
Turkey in the following years. 
</P>
