<HEADLINE> India Adopts Action Plan For IT Sector Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The Information Technology (IT)
Ministers Conference Saturday adopted a 13-point action plan for
rapid growth of the IT sector including zero sales tax and lesser
customs and excise duties on optical fiber, hardware and internet
access devices.
</P>
<P>
As per the action plan, state governments have agreed to offer
zero sales tax facility to IT sector for the next three to five
years, while the central government would reduce customs and
excise duties for optical fiber, IT hardware, set top boxes,
internet access devices and TV sets for education and extension
program.
</P>
<P>
The conference also urged the Internet Service Providers to
extend special tariffs to educational institutes and a flat rate
for other internet subscribers.
</P>
<P>
Information Technology Minister Pramod Mahajan said that the
National highways would offer free Right of Way to access
providers for laying down optical fiber cables wherever the state
governments are extending such facility.
</P>
<P>
The government would speed up decision on setting up private
universities in consultation with state governments, he added.
</P>
<P>
He indicated that facilities for IT and IT-based education
would be expanded and improved by synergizing the expertise of
private sector institutions with those of government and other
established institutions. 
