<HEADLINE> Foundation of 4th EPZ Laid in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Comilla Export Processing Zone,
Bangladesh's fourth export processing zone (EPZ), was inaugurated
by Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina Saturday in Comilla district, some
100 kilometers southeast to the capital city Dhaka, the official
Bangladesh News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
While laying the foundation of the much-awaited Comilla Export
Processing Zone, the prime minister said it would usher in
economic development and prosperity not only for the district, but
also for the country as a whole.
</P>
<P>
To be built on 258 acres adjacent to Comilla Airport, the
Comilla EPZ will create jobs for over 40,000 people on completion.
Some 208 industrial plots will be set up in the Comilla EPZ, of
which works on 40 are to be completed in the first phase.
</P>
<P>
The development works for infrastructure began in April last
year with an estimated cost of 835.6 million taka (16 million U.S.
dollars), and the first-phase works are expected to be finished in
2001, the authorities said, hoping that 3.6 billion taka (69.2
million dollars) will be invested when operations go in full swing.
</P>
<P>
Besides, goods worth 5.9 billion taka (113.46 million dollars)
would be exported from the Comilla EPZ every year, 25 percent of
which would be earned as value-added taxes, officials said.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh now has three export processing zones. Chittagong
EPZ, the first EPZ in the country, started its operation in 1983.
In 1993, another EPZ was set up in Dhaka, the capital city.
</P>
<P>
Investment in Chittagong EPZ has reached 283 million dollars,
while investment in Dhaka EPZ stands at 144 million dollars as on
June 30, 2000.
</P>
<P>
During the last four years, the investment in both EPZs has
increased by 22 percent on an average, and the average growth rate
of export stands at 37 percent.
</P>
<P>
Foundation stone of the third EPZ was laid in 1998 in Mongla, a
southwestern port city in the country, the construction work of
which is going on in full swing.
</P>
<P>
With the successful operation of the Chittagong and Dhaka EPZs,
the present government has also decided to set up another two EPZs
in northern districts for balanced regional development of the
country.
</P>
</TEXT>
