<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Collection of Star Image Posted on Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 15 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. laboratory at the
National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) has started
posting images of the entire nighttime sky on the Internet,
according to a statement reaching here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Some 1.9 million images have been collected by NASA scientists
who observed nighttime skies with special infrared telescopes in
Chile and Arizona in the last three years, the Jet Propulsion
Laboratory statement said.
</P>
<P>
The so-called Two Micron All Sky Survey began in 1997 and is a
joint effort among the University of Massachusetts, the Jet
Propulsion Laboratory at NASA and the California Institute of
Technology.
</P>
<P>
There work, regarded as the largest and most complete star
census to date, produced an online image collection of more than
half a million galaxies and at least 162 million stars. The
collection is large enough to fill 6,000 CD-ROMs.
</P>
<P>
"Any computer with a Web browser can be transformed into a
desktop observatory," said Dr. Michael Skrutskie of the University
of Massachusetts, one of the leading scientists on the project.
</P>
</TEXT>
