<P>
TOKYO -- About 7,000 residents in Japan's Okinawa Prefecture
staged a rally Saturday to protest against two crimes allegedly
committed by U.S. servicemen earlier this month and called for a
reduced U.S. military presence in the prefecture, the Kyodo News
Service reported.
</P>
<P>
It was the largest anti-U.S. forces rally in Japan's
southernmost prefecture since over 85,000 locals demonstrated in
the wake of the rape of a 12-year-old schoolgirl by three U.S.
servicemen in September 1995. (Japan-Okinawa)
