<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Putin's China Visit Helps Cooperation: Ambassador (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Vladimir Putin's
upcoming state visit to China will combine the goodwill of decades
of Sino-Russian friendship with the promise of wider-ranging
bilateral relations in the future, according to the Russian
ambassador to China.
</P>
<P>
"For Russia, China is not only a global power, but a great
neighbor and an important partner in Asia," Igor Rogachev said in
a recent interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
He quoted President Putin as saying that Russia gives priority
to developing its strategic partnership of coordination with China.
</P>
<P>
President Putin will pay his first state visit to China on July
18, as a guest of Chinese President Jiang Zemin.
</P>
<P>
Describing the personal relationship between President Putin
and Chinese President Jiang Zemin as that of "new partners and old
friends," the ambassador said that President Jiang was the first
foreign leader to congratulate Putin on his victory in the Russian
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
In addition to a meeting between President Jiang and President
Putin in the Five-Nation Summit in Dushanbe, the capital city of
Tajikistan in early July, the two leaders will meet in Beijing
again soon.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, they will also have the opportunities to meet on two
other occasions this year, at the millennium summit of heads of
state to be held in the UN headquarters, and at an informal
meeting of leaders of the Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC)
in Brunei.
</P>
<P>
"Frequent contacts between top leaders of the two countries can
be seen as a continuation of the constructive development of
bilateral relations," Rogachev said.
</P>
<P>
Former Russian President Boris Yeltsin, in his eight years in
the Kremlin, established and maintained a good relationship with
the Chinese leadership. President Putin has succeeded in the
tradition of his predecessor. "This shows that Russia will
strengthen political dialogue with the Chinese leaders," Rogachev
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000715.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Putin's China Visit Helps Cooperation: Ambassador (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As a veteran China hand, Rogachev has witnessed the ups and
downs of Sino-Russian relations. In the eight years he has served
as Russian ambassador to China, Sino-Russian relations have
developed steadily.
</P>
<P>
"It is an unchangeable foreign policy of Russia to promote a
strategic partnership of coordination with China," he said, adding
that this policy has been endorsed by main social and political
forces in Russia.
</P>
<P>
During Putin's visit to China, according to the ambassador,
leaders of the two countries are expected to discuss bilateral
cooperation in a variety of areas.
</P>
<P>
Also on the agenda of the presidential talks will be matters
concerning strategic stability in the Asia-Pacific region and the
world at large, the ambassador said.
</P>
<P>
Trade volume between the two countries exceeded 5.7 billion U.S.
dollars last year, an increase of 4.4 percent over a year ago, he
said, adding that the figure in the first five months of this year
increased by 17 percent over the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Of that amount, trade volume between Russia and such northeast
China's provinces as Heilongjiang, Jilin and Liaoning increased by
30 percent. China is now the sixth-largest trading partner of
Russia.
</P>
<P>
"Russia hopes to participate in the development of China's west
by offering high-tech, equipment and energy," he said. Broad
prospects exist for bilateral cooperation in pipelines, nuclear
energy, machinery, aviation, metallurgy and ship-building, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
He said that Sino-Russian economic and trade cooperation needs
to be on an even keel with the political relations of the
countries, thus laying a solid groundwork for the further growth
of bilateral ties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
