<HEADLINE> Iranian Reformist Lawyers Go on Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Two reformist lawyers, Mohsen Rahami
and Shirin Ebadi, went on trial at Branch 16 of Tehran's public
court on Saturday, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The two lawyers, arrested last month, have been accused by the
conservative judiciary of involvement in duplicating and
distributing a videocassette that included "insulting" remarks on
some ranking officials.
</P>
<P>
A source in Tehran's justice department said the trial was held
in camera because of "some documents related to the case that
involve the national security."
</P>
<P>
Rahami, a professor of law at Tehran University, and Ms. Ebadi,
a feminist pro-democracy lawyer, have represented various reformist
clients in high-profile cases.
</P>
<P>
Since the landslide victory of Iranian reformers in February's
parliamentary election, the conservative establishment has never
stopped efforts to crack down on the growing reformist movement.
</P>
<P>
In addition to partially annulling parliamentary election
results, the powerful conservatives have also closed down some 18
reformist papers and journals and arrested a number of journalists
and reformist activists on accusations of violating Islamic values.
</P>
</TEXT>
