<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Ministries Protest Court Verdict on Dorm Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Ministry of Science, Research
and Technology and Ministry of Health and Medical Education on
Saturday protested a recent court verdict issued by the
conservative judiciary on the police attack on Tehran University
dormitory last year.
</P>
<P>
The two ministries in charge of the country's higher education
underlined in a joint statement the need for restoration of the
rights of students, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Acquittal of those accused in the Tehran University dormitory
case raises question about the identity of the real culprits and
agents responsible for beating and injuring students as well as
damaging academic centers, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
It said that the event, called as "catastrophe and crime" by the
supreme leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei and a "national case" by
President Mohammad Khatami, should have been subject to serious and
fair legal and judicial investigation.
</P>
<P>
The scope of financial and spiritual damage done to the
scientific sector can only be evaluated on a national scale and in
connection with national interests and security, the ministries
underlined.
</P>
<P>
The branch 7 of the Tehran military court on Tuesday acquitted
the former commander of Tehran security forces (police) Brigadier
General Farhad Nazari along with 17 other police officers charged
with attacking Tehran University dormitory.
</P>
<P>
The riot police forced into Tehran University dormitory in July
last year, storming student hostels and beating students, following
a student protest against press restrictions.
</P>
<P>
The police attack sparked a six-day political unrest in the
Iranian capital, the worst since the 1979 Islamic Revolution. At
least one died and many others were injured in the riots.
</P>
<P>
Iran's leading reformist party, the Islamic Iran Participation
Front (IIPF), has also criticized the conservative judiciary for
acquitting the main suspects in the dormitory case.
</P>
<P>
The recently-issued court verdict not only failed to meet public
expectations but also disappointed jurists, said the party in an
open letter to the judiciary chief Ayatollah Mahmoud Hashemi
Shahroudi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
