<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The following are the economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey's state-owned railway car maker Tuvasas, based
in the northwestern province of Adapazari, is seeking to merge with
a foreign company due to financial difficulties, reported Turkish
Daily News on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The factory, damaged by the devastating earthquake on August 17
last year, has stopped production since then and is merely doing
repair and maintenance, said Tuvasas General Manager Mehmet
Gokturk.
</P>
<P>
He said, "We are seeking a foreign partner because we have to
compete with global giants. We are going to do whatever it takes to
push Tuvasas forward."
</P>
<P>
The earthquake has rendered 65 percent of the factory non-
operational. Tuvasas employs 1,182 workers and 427 civil servants.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Syria is seeking the installation of a passenger train
between Tehran and Damascus via the Turkish capital Ankara.
</P>
<P>
Mohammad Ayad Gazal, chief of Syrian Railways, made the proposal
in a meeting with his Iranian counterpart Rahman Dadman in Tehran,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian official, who arrived here Friday for a week-long
visit, also expressed hope to make use of Iran's railway technology
in the construction of three express lines in his country.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- A European Commission proposal on July 12 to eliminate
all remaining restrictions on imports of 62 categories of textiles
and clothing products from the European Union (EU) countries by
January 1, 2002 will likely aggravate competition for Turkish
exporters.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Istanbul Textile and Ready-to-Wear Exporters
Union Nuri Artok told the paper that "Turkey faces a price
disadvantage, its products are more expensive."
</P>
<P>
"But it has advantages too, which it should maintain and
enhance. Turkey's geographical proximity, fast-track service,
ability to produce rich quality and sophisticated goods make it a
lucrative exporter to the EU."
</P>
<P>
Turkey's ready-to-wear exports in the first half of 2000 totaled
3.8 billion U.S. dollars and textile exports 1.3 billion dollars.
Out of these figures, 2.6 billion, or 67.2 percent, and 715
million, or 53.6 percent, worth of exports were sent to EU member
states.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The Uzbek Labor Ministry has cancelled the working
licences of 21 Turkish firms working in Uzbekistan on the grounds
that they have not carried out legal requirements.
</P>
<P>
The companies were given six months to wind up their business
activities. The work permits of 66 Turkish citizens who have been
working in these firms have also been revoked.
</P>
<P>
Turkish companies are mostly working in industrial fields such
as textiles, cosmetics, food, furniture and leather.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The European Union (EU) has decided to lift the quotas
imposed on Turkey's textile exports to Europe.
</P>
<P>
EU will phase out the quotas from the year 2002 to 2005, said
Haluk Ozelci, EU representative of the Turkish Textile Ready-to-
Wear Exporters.
</P>
<P>
He said that the year 2005 will be important for Turkish textile
producers and the Turkish textile sector should re-structure itself
and get fully prepared for a new era. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
