<HEADLINE> Former Pakistan Premier Facing Fresh Corruption Charge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's ousted prime minister
Nawaz Sharif is facing another corruption charge as a reference on
one of his estates was presented to the country's accountability
court Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The National Accountability Bureau (NAB) has filed the
reference against the former premier and his parents in the Attock
Fort Accountability Court, which is located in the proximity of
Islamabad, reported the private agency News Network International.
</P>
<P>
The reference questions the source of income for Sharif's
residence at Raiwin near his hometown Lahore, which involved
estimated investment of 247 million rupees (4.7 million U.S.
dollars), the amount not mentioned in the tax returns of the
former prime minister.
</P>
<P>
According to the reference which bears 44 prosecution witnesses,
the construction area of the luxury Raiwind residence is over 5300
square meters with a basement of over 320 square meters. The two-
story building even has a lift.
</P>
<P>
Sharif has been sentenced to life imprisonment in a hijacking
case and being tried in a helicopter corruption case. He might be
tried in more corruption cases.
</P>
<P>
NAB Prosecutor General Farooq Adam Khan said last week that two
more references against the former prime minister, pertaining to a
sugar rebate deal and construction of Lahore-Islamabad motorway
respectively, were also in the pipeline. 
</P>
</TEXT>
