<HEADLINE> French Sea Festival Organizers Urge Release of Russian Yacht </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 15 (Xinhua)-- Organizers of an on-going sea
festival in the western French port of Brest Saturday called for
the release of a Russian yacht which has been detained by French
judicial authorities since Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Agence France-Presse quoted the organizers of the festival,
Brest 2000, as saying that a hearing will be held Saturday by the
Tribunal of Grand Investigation of Brest.
</P>
<P>
Russian yacht "Sedov" was seized because of a lawsuit against
the Russian state by a Swiss import-export company, Noga, which
accused Russia of breaking a contract by refusing to pay 1.4
billion U.S. dollars for the food it sent to Russia in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The 117-meter, four-mast yacht belongs to the University of
Military Technology of Murmansk in northern Russia and has 176
people including 100 cadets of the university and 15 adolescents
from Moscow on board when it arrived in Brest at the invitation of
Brest 2000 organizers.
</P>
<P>
It was seized by the order of bailiffs of the French justice
because they considered the yacht as indirectly owned by the
Russian state, which owns the Murmansk Military Technology
University.
</P>
<P>
If France and Russia fail to reach an agreement on the dispute,
the yacht, which was built in 1921 by the German Krupp, could be
put on auction sale.
</P>
<P>
Russia has urged France to immediately release the yacht or
face serious damage to bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
The French judicial authorities have already frozen some
banking accounts of the Russian diplomatic representations in
France in implementing a verdict by a Swedish court which
represented Noga and decided to seize the property of the Russian
state to pay for its debt to Noga. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
