<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eight Killed, 70 Injured in Tornado Disaster in Western Canada EDS-Update with more information </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Eight people were killed and at
least 70 others injured Friday night when a Tornado hit a summer
campground in central Alberta, Canada.
</P>
<P>
According to latest reports from CTV and other Canadian media,
the tornado descended on the Green Acres campground at Pine Lake
around 7000 p.m. local time.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of light-weight camping trailers were flipped upside
down and even tossed about like toys as the tornado touched down
to turn the campsite into a large pile of twisted metal and broken
wood.
</P>
<P>
There were hundreds of people walking around with scrapes,
bruises while people with serious injuries were being carried out
on strechers, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
"The fatalities are countless at this time. It looks like
something of a rescue camp right now," according to the broadcast
by a TV station in Red Deer, some 60 kilometers northwest of Pine
Lake, which is between the provincial capital Edmonton in the
north and another major city Calgary in the south.
</P>
<P>
Rescue teams have been sent out to the scene of the disaster
from both Edmonton and Calgary, while farmers within a 30-mile (50-
kilometer) radius are flooding the area doing what they can to
help.
</P>
<P>
Alberta Premier Ralph Klein was reported en route to the scene
to join fire, ambulance and emergency crews.
</P>
<P>
The injured were transported to hospitals in Calgary, Edmonton
and Red Deer while rescue divers and police dogs from Calgary were
called in to search for missing people.
</P>
<P>
Environment Canada said the weather system that had spawned the
tornado could be seen from Calgary, about 150 kilometers away.
</P>
<P>
The province was last hit by tornado in 1987, when 27 people
were killed and up to 300 others injured. 
</P>
</TEXT>
