<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thousands of Okinawans Protest Against Crimes by U.S. Servicemen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 15 (Xinhua) -- About 7,000 residents in Japan's
Okinawa Prefecture staged a rally Saturday to protest against two
crimes allegedly committed by U.S. servicemen earlier this month
and called for a reduced U.S. military presence in the prefecture,
the Kyodo News Service reported.
</P>
<P>
It was the largest anti-U.S. forces rally in Japan's
southernmost prefecture since over 85,000 locals demonstrated in
the wake of the rape of a 12-year-old schoolgirl by three U.S.
servicemen in September 1995.
</P>
<P>
On July 3, a U.S. Marine was arrested on suspicion of sexually
assaulting a 14-year-old girl, and a U.S. airman was apprehended
last Sunday in a suspected hit-and-run case.
</P>
<P>
A resolution adopted at the rally called on Washington and U.S.
forces to teach their servicemen about human rights and reduce the
number of troops on U.S. bases in Okinawa, Kyodo reported.
</P>
<P>
It also called for a radical revision of the Japan-U.S. Status
of Forces Agreement which defines the legal status of U.S.
military personnel in Japan.
</P>
<P>
The organizers said they intended to send the resolution to U.S.
President Bill Clinton before the Group of Eight (G-8) summit,
which is slated for July 21-23 in the semitropical island
prefecture, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Okinawan Diet (parliament) members, including ruling Liberal
Democratic Party (LDP) members, former Okinawa Governor Masahide
Ota and mayors of Naha and Ginowan, joined the rally in a park in
the southern Okinawa Island city of Ginowan in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"If the chief of the U.S. forces in Okinawa pledges to double
his efforts (to prevent such incidents), then he must reduce the
number of his troops here to half the current one," Suzuyo
Takazato, a representative of a local women's group against the
military, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The allegations involving the two U.S. servicemen caused an
uproar in Okinawa, where there is strong antipathy to the U.S.
military presence.
</P>
<P>
Residents were especially angered by the alleged assault of the
14-year-old girl, which revived memories of the 1995 rape.
</P>
<P>
Okinawa accounts for only 0.6 percent of Japan's land area but
has some 75 percent of the land occupied by U.S. military
facilities in Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
