<HEADLINE> Sino-Foreign Human Genome Research Project Launched in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese National Human Genome
Center (CHGC) and pharmaceutical multinational Roche (China) today
signed an agreement for co-operation in human genome research for
schizophrenia and diabetes.
</P>
<P>
CHGC Director Chen Zhu said it is the researchers' hope that
the project will help in the development of genic medicines for
the diseases, which are expected to become the major health risks
for China's growing aged population.
</P>
<P>
Roche will provide 300,000 U.S. dollars as well as technical
support and personnel training in the next three years for the
project.
</P>
<P>
All data and results of the research will become the joint
property of the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The CHGC is a major Chinese participant in working draft of the
Human Genome Project.
</P>
<P>
Roche now has six joint ventures and a solely-funded company in
China producing pharmaceuticals, vitamins, fine chemicals and
other products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
