<DOCNO> XIE20000715.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Embargo Kills over 8,000 Iraqis in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The decade-old U.N. sanctions
against Iraq claimed lives of more than 8,000 Iraqis in June,
bringing the total number of victims to 1,324,760 since 1990, the
Iraqi Health Ministry announced Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said in a statement that 5,511 children under the
age of five died of diarrhea, pneumonia, respiratory infections and
malnutrition last month.
</P>
<P>
And 2,671 elderly people died of heart diseases, hypertension,
diabetes and malignant neoplasms.
</P>
<P>
Such a high mortality rate, due to malnutrition and severe
medicine shortage caused by the sanctions, was in sharp contrast
with the same month in 1989, when some 387 children and 434 elderly
people died.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has repeatedly called on the U.N. to unconditionally lift
the stringent sanctions, imposed on it after its 1990 invasion of
Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
And Iraq has long accused the United States and Britain of
impeding the implementation of the U.N. oil-for-food program by
deliberately blocking contracts Iraq signed with foreign countries
to buy food, medicine and other humanitarian supplies.
</P>
<P>
In December 1996, the U.N. started to implement the humanitarian
oil-for-food program in Iraq, which allows Iraq to sell limited
amount of oil every six months to buy humanitarian supplies for its
people reeling under the sanctions. 
</P>
<P>
Hans Von Sponeck, former U.N. humanitarian coordinator in Iraq,
and Jutta Burghardt, former representative of the World Food
Program, resigned in February in protest against the continuing
sanctions and the worsening humanitarian situation in Iraq.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
