<HEADLINE> Singapore to Recruit Teachers from Well Educated Singaporeans: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 15 (Xinhua) --Singapore Minister for Education
Teo Chee Hean has affirmed that his ministry aims to recruit new
teachers from the top one-third of educated Singaporeans of each
cohort so as to achieve a good overall quality of his country's
teaching force.
</P>
<P>
The minister who doubles as the Second Minister for Defense
made the point at the 2nd Teaching Scholarship Presentation
Ceremony here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The government must make sure that the teaching service will
have some of the best of each cohort come into the teaching force,
he emphasized.
</P>
<P>
He said his ministry has invested substantially in teaching
scholarships and awards so as to attract the best young people to
come into teaching and make teaching an attractive career choice.
</P>
<P>
The number of the Ministry of Education (MOE) scholarships and
awards given out has doubled within the last three years from 133
in 1997 to 375 this year, he underlined.
</P>
<P>
He also said that his ministry has recruited 7,000 officers
over the last three years and this represents more than a quarter
of his country's teaching force of 23,500.
</P>
<P>
he noted that Singapore's teaching service has seen significant
improvements in pay, promotion prospects and professional
upgrading opportunities since 1996, citing MOE introduced new
intermediate grades to give teachers additional promotional
opportunities and a faster first promotion starting in January of
this year and the teaching service received an average 13 percent
increase in salaries since two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Teo also said that his country needs a new generation of
teachers to propel education system into 21st century, noting that
3,500 teachers now in their 50s will retire in the next five years,
accounting for 30 percent of the total teaching force.
</P>
<P>
The task ahead now is to ensure that the education system
continues to do well even as the more experienced ones retire, he
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
