<HEADLINE> Feature: "Snakeheads Almost Killed Me," Says Fujian Stowaway (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"But it was too early for us to be merry," Dong said. "Another
nightmare was waiting."
</P>
<P>
They drove for more than 20 hours non-stop. Dong said they
nearly suffocated in the close quarters.
</P>
<P>
"Several persons vomited and relieved themselves inside, making
the already turbid air even worse."
</P>
<P>
The van finally stopped in a forest, where several husky men
led them to a thatched hut. They slept on the floor and ate more
black dough. The next day, a Chinese and a Russian came to see
them, saying the only way out was to call their families in Fujian
to say they had arrived at their destinations and needed money.
</P>
<P>
"The snakeheads ordered us to tell our relatives to mail 200,
000 yuan to a certain account number, otherwise we would never
return home," Dong said.
</P>
<P>
When they refused to pay, they were beaten. Dong was knocked
unconscious.
</P>
<P>
From that day on, the captors threatened the group every day,
frequently inflicting serious injuries.
</P>
<P>
Ye Fang, a young woman from Fuzhou, said that the snakeheads
humiliated them in every way imaginable.
</P>
<P>
"Once they beat me, and my face was swollen and red for more
than a week," she said. "I am still suffering from a ringing in my
ears. Sometimes I can't hear."
</P>
<P>
Realizing that escape was the only way to freedom, they took
their chances one rainy night when their guards were asleep and
ran. At dawn they found themselves in Ukraine, where they
contacted the Chinese embassy. With its assistance they returned
to China on May 16, ending a four-month nightmare.
</P>
<P>
Police in Fujian investigated their stories and charged them
according to law. Dong was held by police for 15 days and fined 5,
000 yuan for illegally crossing the border into Russia.
</P>
<P>
"Snakeheads are liars," Dong said. "I will never be a stowaway
again."  
</P>
</TEXT>
