<HEADLINE> Foreign Exchange Reserves Fall in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 15 (Xinhua) -- India's foreign exchange
reserves fell by 63 million U.S. dollars to 36.667 billion dollars
for the week ended on July 7, 2000, as compared to the previous
week.
</P>
<P>
It was only in the previous week ended June 30, 2000, that the
reserves rose by 260 million dollars to 36.730 billion dollars
after 10 weeks' continuous decline.
</P>
<P>
According to the Reserve Bank of India, the fall in the
reserves was on account of foreign currency assets (FCA) dwindling
by 63 million dollars in the reporting week to 33.711 billion
dollars compared to the previous week.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, special drawing rights and gold reserves of the
country remained static at 8 million dollars and 2.948 billion
dollars, respectively, it added. 
</P>
