<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Judiciary Under Fire for Verdict on Dorm Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 15 (Xinhua) -- One of Iran's leading reformist
parties, the Islamic Iran Participation Front (IIPF), has
criticized the conservative judiciary for acquitting the main
suspects in last year's student dormitory incident which sparked
nation-wide riots.
</P>
<P>
The court verdict on the university dorm case not only failed to
meet public expectations but also disappointed jurists, said the
party in an open letter to the judiciary chief, Ayatollah Mahmoud
Hashemi Shahroudi.
</P>
<P>
The official IRNA news agency reported on Saturday that the
party expressed regret over the so-called irregularities in the
court proceedings, noting the verdict on the dorm case may lead
people to doubt the effectiveness of the judiciary system in
restoring calm and security in the society.
</P>
<P>
The Branch Seven of Tehran's military court on Tuesday handed
down a verdict acquitting former chief of Tehran police, Farhad
Nazari, along with 17 other policemen of all charges against them
for forcibly entering a Tehran University dormitory on July 8 last
year.
</P>
<P>
The police raid on the students aimed to disperse protests
against press restrictions imposed by the conservative authorities,
but the clashes triggered six-day riots, the worst Iran has
experienced since the 1979 Islamic revolution. At least one people
died and many others injured in the riots.
</P>
<P>
The IIPF is led by President Mohammad Khatami's brother Mohammad
Reza Khatami, who is deputy speaker of the reformist-controlled
Majlis (parliament). The party and other reformist organizations
maintain that the dormitory case should be thoroughly investigated
and all those responsible be punished. 
</P>
</TEXT>
