<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU's Evaluation of Turkey's Reforms Mixed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Guenter Verheugen, the European
Union (EU) commissioner for Enlargement Affairs, gave mixed
evaluation about Turkey's reforms for EU membership since it was
granted candidacy last December.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner paid a visit to Ankara this week. At a press
conference on Thursday, he expressed satisfaction with the pace of
harmonization reforms in Turkey to join the European club.
</P>
<P>
But later during his meetings with representatives of human
rights organizations and non-governmental organizations (NGOs)
concerned with democratization, Verheugen criticized Ankara for
lack of improvements on human rights.
</P>
<P>
It has been learned that Verheugen told NGO representatives that
no substantial progress on reforms regarding human rights had been
achieved in Turkey since last December's Helsinki Summit decided to
open the rich-nation club to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Verheugen reportedly stressed that the lack of improvements has
created uneasiness within the EU, adding that the EU had expected a
rapid reform program from Ankara in the wake of the summit.
</P>
<P>
He indicated that the EU had not seen a determined political
will on the Turkish side to go ahead with the political reforms
imperative to fulfill the Copenhagen criteria for EU membership.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner warned that if Turkey does not speed up its
efforts, the approval of the accession partnership that is expected
to be carried out at the beginning of November could be in
jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
It was learned that Verheugen carefully took notes during his
meetings with NGO representatives, which lasted for nearly one and
a half hour.
</P>
<P>
He told Turkish officials in charge of EU affairs that the EU
expects Turkey's structural reforms to be achieved very soon.
</P>
<P>
Verheugen's remarks during his meetings with the NGOs were in
contrast with his statement at Thursday's press conference where he
said that Turkey was on the right track in its efforts towards EU
membership.
</P>
<P>
He only vaguely touched on the issue of Kurdish-populated
southeast, adding that the EU was against capital punishment and
was working to abolish it worldwide.
</P>
<P>
The EU has been urging Turkey to abolish the death penalty in
its laws and respect rights of ethnic Kurds in culture and other
fields.
</P>
<P>
Verheugen had an intensive agenda in Ankara on Friday as he met
almost all the high-level Turkish authorities, including President
Ahmet Necdet Sezer, Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit and Mesut Yilmaz,
the newly appointed deputy prime minister and state minister
responsible for EU affairs.
</P>
<P>
During his talks with Yilmaz, Verheugen said the main topic was
human rights. After he was briefed on human rights reforms in
Turkey, he told Yilmaz that "political will" is very important in
pursuing such reforms.
</P>
<P>
Verheugen will submit a report on Turkey to the EU Commission by
October. The report will be based on to create an accession
partnership for the country.
</P>
<P>
The accession partnership, which means a step forward in
Turkey's process to membership, is expected to be approved in
November by the EU Council of General Affairs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
