<DOCNO> XIE20000715.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 20 MILF Members Offered Safe Conduct Passes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government announced
Saturday that it has granted safe conduct passes to 20 members of
the Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) as part of its efforts to
facilitate the resumption of formal peace talks with the group.
</P>
<P>
Those granted safe conduct passes include members of the MILF
peace negotiation team, their consultants and advisers and
technical working staff, government peace panel chairman Edgaro
Batenga said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The passes will take effect on July 20 and last "for the
duration of the peace talks," he said.
</P>
<P>
"This signals the government's commitment to pursue a lasting
peace and ensure the attainment of the full potentials of
development in Mindanao," said Batenga.
</P>
<P>
President Joseph Estrada has earlier ordered to issue safety
and security guarantees to MILF members involved in peace
negotiations with the government.
</P>
<P>
Those MILF members "shall not be restrained, searched, seized
and harassed on their persons or property in connection with their
participation or involvement in the peace process, except in cases
of commission of common crimes, such as crimes against persons,
chastity, property and other similar offenses," according to the
statement.
</P>
<P>
The government said it remains hopeful that the stalled peace
talks between the government and the MILF can be resumed on July
29 to discuss an autonomy proposal it offered to the rebel group,
which has been fighting for an independent Islamic state in the
southern island of Mindanao for two decades.
</P>
<P>
In late June the government agreed to extend for 29 days the
June 30 deadline set by President Estrada for the MILF to sign a
peace deal with the government, but on conditions that the MILF
abandon its bid for independence and stop terrorist acts.
</P>
<P>
After the MILF rejected the government demands and failed to
meet the deadline, the military began launching attacks on Camp
Abubakar, the rebel group's headquarters in Matanog in the
province of Maguindanao, Mindanao, and captured the rebel
stronghold last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
MILF chairman Hashim Salamat called on fellow Muslims to wage a
jihad or holy war across the country after the fall of Camp
Abubakar.
</P>
<P>
The government said Friday that it may "seriously consider"
granting Salamat a safe conduct pass should he decide to
participate in the peace negotiations and withdraw his call for a
jihad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
