<HEADLINE> Weekly Highlights of Diplomatic News (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Vice-President of Ghana John Evans Atta Mills arrived in
Beijing Monday for a week-long official visit to China, at the
invitation of Chinese Vice-President Hu Jintao.
</P>
<P>
Chinese, Ghanaian Vice-Presidents Hold Talks
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice-President Hu Jintao Tuesday told his visiting
Ghanaian counterpart John Evans Atta Mills during their talks that
China hopes to work together with Ghana to bring Sino-Ghanaian
friendship and relations of cooperation which are vital, stable,
and comprehensive into the 21st Century.
</P>
<P>
As developing countries, China and Ghana face the common task
of safeguarding national sovereignty and integrity while at the
same time developing their economies, he noted. It is therefore in
the interests of both sides to make the most of their mutual
goodwill and deepen bilateral cooperation in all fields.
</P>
<P>
Hu expressed satisfaction with the progress of bilateral
relations since the two countries established diplomatic ties 40
years ago.
</P>
<P>
 Chinese President Meets Ghanaian Vice-President
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin said Tuesday China and Ghana
should continue to promote bilateral relationship 40 years after
it has been forged.
</P>
<P>
New progress has been made in all-round cooperation between the
two countries in recent years, said Jiang in a meeting with
visiting Ghanaian Vice-President John Evans Atta Mills.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese president described Ghana as "an old friend." Even
with great changes taking place internationally and domestically,
China and Ghana have furthered their friendly and cooperative
relations in line of mutual understanding and respect, equal
treatment and sincere cooperation, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
 Ghanaian Vice-President Visits Shenzhen and Qingdao
</P>
<P>
Visiting Ghanaian Vice-President John Evans Atta Mills left
Beijing Wednesday for Shenzhen in south China's Guangdong province.
</P>
<P>
He also visited Qingdao city in eastern China's Shandong
province Friday.
</P>
<P>
Ghanaian Vice-President Leaves China
</P>
<P>
Ghanaian Vice-President John Evans Atta Mills concluded his
week-long official visit to China and left Beijing Saturday
afternoon.
</P>
</TEXT>
