<HEADLINE> Weekly Highlights of Diplomatic News (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
U.S. Defense Secretary William Sebastian Cohen arrived in
Beijing Tuesday afternoon, kicking off his five-day visit to China.
</P>
<P>
Cohen paid the visit at the invitation of his Chinese
counterpart Chi Haotian.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Meets Cohen
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin said Thursday that a healthy and
stable growth of Sino-U.S. relations not only accords with the
fundamental interests of the people of the two countries, but also
is conducive to the peace in the Asia-Pacific and the world at
large.
</P>
<P>
Jiang, who is also chairman of the Central Military Commission,
made the remarks while meeting with visiting U.S. Defense
Secretary William Cohen.
</P>
<P>
Vice-President Meets Cohen
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice-President Hu Jintao emphasized to visiting U.S.
Defense Secretary William Cohen that if the relationship between
China and the U.S. is to grow in the right direction, it is
essential for the United States to strictly observe the principles
outlined in the three China-U.S. joint communiques and properly
handle the Taiwan issue.
</P>
<P>
Hu made the remarks when meeting with Cohen Wednesday afternoon
at the Beijing's Great Hall of the People.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Premier meets Cohen
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice Premier Qian Qichen, in a meeting with visiting
Defense Secretary of the United States William Cohen, emphasized
Thursday that the proper settlement of the Taiwan issue is the key
to maintaining healthy and stable China-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
 Chinese, U.S. Defense Ministers Hold Talks
</P>
<P>
Evasion of the One-China principle has no way out, and Taiwan
issue can not and will not be delayed indefinitely, said Chinese
Defense Minister Chi Haotian Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Sino-U.S. relationship is facing opportunities and problems as
well, and the most important and sensitive of the problems is the
Taiwan issue," Chi said in a meeting with U.S. Defense Secretary
William Cohen.
</P>
<P>
 CMC Official Meets Cohen
</P>
<P>
With so many profound changes taking place globally, Sino-U.S.
relations need to advance on a healthy, stable track, Zhang
Wannian, vice-chairman of the Central Military Commission (CMC),
told visiting U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen during talks
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
PLA Official Meets Cohen
</P>
<P>
The Chinese People's Liberation Army (PLA) firmly supports the
Chinese government's stand on the Taiwan issue, and is fully
confident, determined, and capable of safeguarding national
sovereignty, territorial integrity and national dignity, said Fu
Quanyou, chief of the PLA General Staff, Wednesday while meeting
with visiting U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen.
</P>
<P>
ARATS President Meets Cohen
</P>
<P>
Wang Daohan, president of the Association for Relations Across
the Taiwan Straits, met Friday with William Cohen, defense
secretary of the United States, and the two sides held talks on
the Taiwan issue.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Defense Secretary Leaves China
</P>
<P>
U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen concluded his five-day
visit to China and left Shanghai Saturday morning.
</P>
</TEXT>
