<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Governor Election Won't Affect Bangkok's Bid: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The change of Bangkok's governor
will not affect the capital's bid for the 2008 Olympics, an
official of the Bangkok Olympic Bid Organizing Committee (BOBOC)
said here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The bid campaign will continue, and will be supported by
whoever was elected as governor on July 23, Tirachai Vutithum, who
oversees the advertising campaign and public survey of the BOBOC.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the officials in charge of the bid campaign
will continue to hold office as they had been appointed by the
Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
"Hosting the Olympics will help the country's economy. So
whoever becomes the new governor should support the bid," he
stated.
</P>
<P>
The five finalists for holding the Games will be announced on
August 29. Tirachai said the original plan had been to set up the
company responsible for handling the bidding ahead of that date.
But the BOBOC had now decided to start the process early and
submit its proposal to the Cabinet ahead of the results.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on Bangkok's chances of winning the first-round bid,
Tirachai said that the city had a good chance of making it to the
second round.
</P>
<P>
"There are seven International Olympic Committee (IOC) members
who have the right to vote and one of them is a German, who I am
certain will vote for Bangkok in return of our vote which help
Germany clinch the 2006 soccer World Cup bid, " he added.
</P>
<P>
"Besides, none of the bidding cities have hosted the Olympics,
which gives each one of them an equal chance."
</P>
<P>
He believed that if Bangkok was chosen to be one of the five
finalists, private companies will come forward with their support.
General Chetta Thanajaro, chairman of the country's Olympic
Committee,had offered to help in this regard.
</P>
<P>
"The budget for the second-round bid is estimated at around 500
million baht (12.5 million US dollars), but we might not be able
to generate such a huge sum without good support from the private
sector," Tirachai said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Tourism Authority of Thailand's development
service director, Wansadet Tawornsuk, confirmed that the authority
will start overseas promotion of the bid if Bangkok wins the
second round.  
</P>
</TEXT>
