</P>
<P>
Sino-Lao ties have developed rapidly since the normalization of
relations between the two countries, said Li Peng, chairman of the
Standing Committee of the National People's Congress (NPC), in
meeting with visiting Lao President Khamtay Siphandone Friday.
</P>
<P>
Li said Khamtay's current visit to China at the turn of a new
century is of important political significance and will further
deepen the bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
 Chinese Premier Meets Laotian President
</P>
<P>
Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji in his meeting with visiting Lao
President Khamtay Siphandone said Friday that China is willing to
develop cooperative areas and projects beneficial to both China
and Laos.
</P>
<P>
After reviewing the gradual expansion of Chinese investment and
labor projects in Laos, Zhu told the Lao president that there is
still great potential to tap between the two sides. He called on
relevant organs, economic and trade departments in particular, to
"explore new ways and ideas" for cooperative areas and projects
which have "market demand" and "economic returns" and are
beneficial to the "long-term growth" of the Lao economy.
</P>
<P>
Laotian President Leaves for Home
</P>
<P>
Laotian President Khamtay Siphandone today concluded his three-
day state visit to China and left for home Saturday after a short
stay in Kunming, capital city of southwest China's Yunnan province.
