<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Sons Of Alcoholic Men Have Lower IQ </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The sons of alcoholic fathers,
especially fathers who also have antisocial personality disorder,
are at greater risk for intellectual and academic deficits than
other boys are, according to a study released Friday.
</P>
<P>
The study, conducted by researchers at Michigan State
University and published in the July issue of Alcoholism: Clinical
and Experimental Research, analyzed 198 elementary school-age boys.
</P>
<P>
Two thirds of the boys came from families with alcoholic
fathers. The children were grouped according to whether they had
alcoholic fathers with antisocial personalities (AAL), alcoholic
fathers without such tendencies (NAAL), or fathers without alcohol
problems.
</P>
<P>
Edwin Poon, author of the study, said he and his colleagues
found that, in virtually every measure of intellectual and
academic function, AAL boys scored significantly lower than boys
without alcoholic parents. Their IQs, while clearly within the
normal range, were lower, and these boys were more distractible,
had more difficulty with mazes, and did not perform as well on
spelling and arithmetic tests.
</P>
<P>
NAAL boys had somewhat lower overall IQ scores and performed
less well than boys from nonalcoholic families in arithmetic,
according to the investigators.
</P>
<P>
"We've continued to follow these kids, and many of them are
about to enter adolescence," Poon said. "We should have more to
report in the next year or two regarding whether our predictions
for these children of alcoholics hold up." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000715.0109 </DOCNO>
