<HEADLINE> International Sand Sculpture Festival in East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHOUSHAN, (ZHEJIANG) July 15 (Xinhua) -- An international sand
sculpture festival kicked off today at the Golden Beach of
Zhujiajian, an islet east off Zhoushan Island, east China's
Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
A total of 23 sand sculptures, which were created by Chinese
and overseas masters in the past eight days, are shown at the
festival, the second of its kind and featuring the theme of "
miracles of the century".
</P>
<P>
Pavel Zadaniouk from Russia won the first prize for his work
among the international competitors' group, while Zhao Baokang
from east China's Shanghai was also given a top prize in the
domestic competitors' group.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the competitions, the festival will include
other activities such as exhibitions of the sand and ice
sculptures, tours to the state ecological park at Zhujiajian and
pilgrimages to Mount Putuo, one of China's four famous Buddhist
shrines, and a photographic contest on sand sculpture.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, the first Zhoushan international
sand sculpture festival, which was held last October, brought
about 100 million yuan in total income to Zhoushan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
