<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Pregnant Women Infected with HIV in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Thailand witnesses a rise in the
HIV infection among pregnant women in recent two to three years,
not long after it won applause for the epidemic prevention from
the United Nations, the Bangkok Post reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The latest report of the Public Health Ministry's epidemiology
division showed that 1.76 percent of pregnant women were infected
with HIV last year against 1.53 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
While the overall picture showed the HIV rate among pregnant
women to be 1.76 percent, the rate was 5.91 percent in the North,
2.02 percent in the Central region, 1.92 percent in the South and
1.25 percent in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
The rate among Thai pregnant women peaked at 2.29 percent in
1995, then gradually declined to 1.81 percent in 1996 and 1.68
percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The report coincided with United Nation's Children's Fund's (
UNICEF) Progress of Nations 2000 report released recently.
</P>
<P>
Gamini Abeysekera, the UNICEF representative in Thailand, said
the report stressed the need to mobilize all sectors of society.
Adolescents constituted the most vulnerable age group due to
ignorance of the need for safe sex, he said.
</P>
<P>
Thai Public Health Minister Korn Dabbaransi said efforts were
under way to reduce vertical HIV-positive transmission from women
to their newborn.
</P>
<P>
By making anti-retroviral drugs available to HIV-positive
pregnant women, Korn said, HIV infection among infants had been
reduced from 25 percent in recent years to 7.5 percent today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000715.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Strong Quake Rocks Japan's Niijima Island </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 15 (Xinhua) -- A powerful earthquake measuring 6.2
on the Richter scale jolted Niijima Island and nearby islands
south of Tokyo on Saturday morning, injuring two people and
causing landslides, the Meteorological Agency said.
</P>
<P>
The two people suffered minor injuries in the quake, which
occurred at 10.30 a.m. (0130 GMT), the agency said, adding that
several landslides were observed on the islands, and 700
households suffered power cuts.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese government set up a task force at the prime
minister's official residence at 11 a.m. (0200 GMT) to cope with
the quake and monitor the situation in affected areas.
</P>
<P>
The quake was also felt in various parts of eastern and central
Japan including Tokyo, Yokohama, Chiba and Nagano prefectures.
</P>
<P>
The epicenter of the tremor was estimated at 10 kilometers
under the sea near Niijima and Kozushima, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Landslides on Niijima covered part of a road and destroyed at
least one home, the Kyodo news agency quoted local officials as
saying.
</P>
<P>
About 200 residents were seeking refuge in Niijima's Wakago
medical center after the quake, Kyodo quoted local police as
saying.
</P>
<P>
On Japan's largest main island of Honshu, train service on the
Tokaido Shinkansen Line was suspended between Mishima and Shizuoka
stations following the quake, but resumed 10 minutes later, the
news agency said.
</P>
<P>
The strong quake occurred shortly after Mt. Oyama, the 813-
meter volcano at the center of Miyakejima Island, erupted again.
</P>
<P>
The Meteorological Agency said the eruption took place at 6.37
a.m. (2137 GMT Friday) on the island, which lies some 180
kilometers south of Tokyo. The volcano erupted on July 8 and 14.
</P>
</TEXT>
