<HEADLINE> Philippines' Payatas dumpsite death toll rises to 148 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 15, (Xinhua) -- The death toll in a trash dumpsite
landslide in Metro Manila has risen to 148 as rescuers recovered
the body of a teenage boy at the site early Saturday morning,
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
The number of people missing can not be determined yet after
Monday's massive landslide at the Payatas garbage dumpsite in
Quezon City, said the National Disaster Coordinating Council.
</P>
<P>
According to a local TV report, more than 180 people might
still be buried in the heap of rubbish after the avalanche, which
was set off by heavy rains from recent typhoons.
</P>
<P>
The council said rescuers have found 59 survivors so far and
496 families or 2,280 persons have been evacuated to safe places.
Sixty people were injured in the tragedy, it added.
</P>
<P>
Health Secretary Alberto Romualdez on Friday warned scavengers
who refused to leave Payatas to get out of the dumpsite or face
the danger of inhaling toxic fumes being emitted by the huge pile
of garbage and other hazardous materials.
</P>
<P>
There were reportedly 50,000 people residing in Payatas. The
open dumpsite was scheduled to be closed in 1999, but the closure
was held back for lack of an alternative disposal site for Quezon
City 's more than 700 tons of daily garbage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
