<HEADLINE> Palestinians Accuse U.S. of Isolating Arafat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinians accused Friday
the U.S. hosts of attempting to isolate Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat and his delegation in talks with Israel in a bid to
pressure them into concessions.
</P>
<P>
"This is not the best form of negotiation, to isolate President
Arafat from the (Palestinian Liberation Organization or PLO)
executive committee and his constituency," Palestinian spokeswoman
Hanan Ashrawi said, referring to U.S. refusal of some Palestinian
leaders' demand to see Arafat at Camp David, Maryland.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has invited a dozen senior Palestinian leaders,
including ministers, PLO executive committee members and
opposition leaders, to the heavily guarded U.S. presidential
retreat to consult on the peace negotiations with Israel.
</P>
<P>
To pacify the Palestinians' discontent, Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright on Friday went to the town of Emmitsburg, 12
kilometers north of Camp David, to meet with six Palestinian
leaders who had flown in to consult with Arafat.
</P>
<P>
But Albright gave no commitment that they would be allowed into
Camp David.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian Minister of Parliamentary Affairs Nabil Amr, who
refused to meet Albright, said: "We are here to meet with
President Arafat, not Madeleine Albright."
</P>
<P>
"This is an interference in Palestinian internal affairs and we
perceive it as an attempt to isolate the negotiators and force
concessions on the Palestinian side," Amr said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to a code of secrecy agreed by all delegations at
Camp David, White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said that "Given
the spirit of the ground rules we put down, we indicated that we
prefer that the meeting (with Arafat) not happen up at Camp David.
"
</P>
<P>
He explained that Washington did not want to disturb the "
positive atmosphere" at the presidential retreat.
</P>
<P>
However, the U.S. hosts did allow Dan Meridor, former Israeli
finance minister and now a member of parliament, to enter Camp
David and join the Israeli delegation two days after the summit
began.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton opened the summit with Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat on
Tuesday at David Camp, hoping that his mediation could help solve
the decades-long conflict between Israel and the Palestinians and
reach a final status agreement between the two sides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
