<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State Cuts Number of Staff By Half </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 15 (Xinhua) -- About 2.5 million public servants,
about half of those hired by local governments throughout China,
have been laid off during the ongoing government restructuring, "
China Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
This was the latest update on the effort to streamline
government into a highly efficient force of expert civil servants.
The reform was first completed by the end of 1998 at State-level
agencies.
</P>
<P>
Song Defu, minister of personnel, confirmed the number of the
laid-off government employees at a seminar yesterday on public
administration reform in Asia, attended by some 50 scholars and
practitioners from 12 Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
Central and local government staff once totaled 5.5 million,
said Wang Feng, director-general of the State Commission Office
for Public Service Structure and Establishment, in his report.
</P>
<P>
During the central government level reform, the number of
employees was cut by half from 32,000 to 16,000, including nearly
40 ministers and over 550 bureau directors.
</P>
<P>
In the future, local governments at provincial, city and county
levels will follow suit, reducing their staff by about 50 percent,
according to Wang.
</P>
<P>
Experts said overstaffing has caused low efficiency and
additional financial burdens. The economic globalization has
prompted Asian countries to speed up the reform of public
administration, they said.
</P>
<P>
By exchanging reform experiences with other Asian countries,
Song said he hopes "China can also share the achievements of
reform with them."
</P>
<P>
"It is of vital importance for China to push forward and ensure
a sustainable development of economy through intensifying the
reform of administration and building a capable government with
high efficiency," Song said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
