<HEADLINE> Indonesian Military Told to Punish Troops Involved in Riot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Defense Minister Juwono
Sudarsono has asked the Military (TNI) to punish troops involved
in the riot in Maluku and North Maluku provinces.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that elements outside Maluku wanted the riots
in Maluku to continue.
</P>
<P>
"The truth is, the people of Ambon (capital of Maluku) and
Maluku, whether Muslims or Christians, are exhausted after
brawling for almost two years. Every time efforts are made to find
a peaceful solution, there is always a disturbance from a third
party from outside Maluku," Sudarsono was quoted by the Indonesian
Observer Saturday as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Military and the House of Representatives (DPR) Friday held
an evaluation meeting here to discuss the latest development in
Maluku and North Maluku.
</P>
<P>
Sudarsono said the evaluation meeting agreed to repatriate
those who were not supposed to be there, and who were apparently
involved in the riot.
</P>
<P>
The meeting agreed that the state of civil emergency in the two
provinces should remain intact and ruled out the possibility of
imposing martial law to stop the continuing clashes there.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also resulted in an agreement to intensify gun
sweeps, forcing Laskar Jihad (Jihad Force) Muslim volunteers to
quit the islands.
</P>
<P>
Sudarsono said he has asked TNI Chief Admiral Widodo A.S. and
Army Chief General Tyasno Sudarto to evaluate the involvement of
Army troops in the communal riots in Maluku and North Maluku.
</P>
<P>
"Neutral" security personnel would be sent to Maluku to replace
the personnel who had taken sides with the warring groups, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The government would rely on the Navy to apprehend Laskar Jihad
members and remove them from the provinces on the grounds that
they had ignited fresh clashes there.
</P>
<P>
"The dispatch of Laskar Jihad and any other forces has reached
almost 10,000 people in the last three months and they have become
the main reason for the ongoing ground conflict," he added.
</P>
<P>
Sporadic clashes have continued despite the state of emergency
imposed last month in the Maluku and North Maluku provinces, where
18-month fighting between Muslims and Christians has claimed more
than 3,000 lives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
