<HEADLINE> Indonesian Army Involved in 1996 PDI Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The Joint Investigating Team
tasked to investigate the attack against the headquarters of the
Indonesian Democratic party (PDI) on July 27, 1996, has affirmed
the involvement of the military in the bloody incident.
</P>
<P>
The involvement of the military was based on information given
by around 40 witnesses, the Indonesian Observer daily Saturday
quoted an official of the National Police as saying.
</P>
<P>
"I cannot as yet mention any names now," Deputy Director for
General Crimes at the National Police headquarters Senior
Superintendent Makbul patmanegara said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The joint team consists of officials from the National Police
Headquarters, the Military Police Office and the National Defense
Forces (TNI).
</P>
<P>
Top military officials who have been investigated by the police
include former military commander Feisal Tanjung, former Army
chief Hartono, former Military chief of Social and Political
Affairs Syarwan Hamid and former Jakarta Military Commander
Sutiyoso.
</P>
<P>
The July 27 attack was committed by supporters of the then
government-backed PDI Chairman Soerjadi as they failed to evict
supporters of the toppled PDI chairwoman Megawati Soekarnoputri
occupying the building at Jalan Diponegoro in central Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
During the attack, dozens of people belonging to supporters of
Megawati (now Indonesia's vice president) were killed or missing.
</P>
<P>
Buttu Hutapea, the then secretary general of the Soerjadi-led
PDI later told police interrogators that the attack was originally
launched by the military.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Sutiyoso, who is now Jakarta governor, said that the
attack on the PDI office was decided "at the national level."
</P>
<P>
Three former top officials of the PDI have been named as
suspects, including Soerjadi and Hutapea. But so far no military
officials have been named suspects.
</P>
<P>
The joint team will start questioning next Monday military
personnel about their possible roles in the violent crime, police
and military officers said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
