<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dutchman Comeback to Win Rhode Island Tennis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Peter Wessels of the
Netherlands recovered a five month illness absence to outlast
fourth-seeded Jonas Bjorkman to reach the semifinals of the Hall
of Fame Tennis Championships in Newport of Rhode Island on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Wessels took the game in 7-6 (7-5) 6-3 and will face will face
seventh-seeded Australian Wayne Arthurs, who trounced Mardy Fish,
6-3, 6-2, in Saturday's semifinals.
</P>
<P>
Off the circuit from December until May with an undetermined
illness he described as "over-tiredness," the slender 6-4 Wessels
authored the upset with a solid serve-and volley game and some
highly consistent returns.
</P>
<P>
Wessels took a 6-3 lead in the first set tiebreaker, then
yielded the next two points.
</P>
<P>
Finally, with Bjorkman serving, Wessels ripped a passing shot
down the line to take the set.
</P>
<P>
Bjorkman, who went into the quarterfinals as the highest
remaining seed, felt he lost confidence in his return game.
</P>
<P>
Arthurs fired 16 aces in his runaway over Fish, an 18-year-old
Floridian who turned pro a year ago and was playing in his first
career quarterfinal. As might be expected, he had troubles
returning.
</P>
<P>
Fish had raised some eyebrows here Thursday by putting out top-
seeded defending champion Chris Woodruff.
</P>
<P>
In the other semifinal bracket, which was determined Thursday,
fifth-seeded Jason Stoltenberg of Australia will oppose unseeded
Jens Knippschild of Germany. 
</P>
</TEXT>
