<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Review of Top Legal News Events in China (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chinese legislators have passed an amendment to the law on
product quality, aiming to upgrade the level of China-made
products.
</P>
<P>
Li Chuanqing, director of the State Bureau of Quality and
Technical Supervision, said that the revised law further defines
the responsibility for the government to improve product quality
and stresses that enterprises must accept supervision from the
quality control departments.
</P>
<P>
Former CITIC Official Denied Appeal for Life in Prison
</P>
<P>
The Higher People's Court of Beijing on July 7 denied an appeal
by Jin Deqin, former deputy chairperson of the board for the China
International Trust and Investment Corporation (CITIC), who was
sentenced to life in prison for embezzlement.
</P>
<P>
On June 2, Jin was given a life term and deprived of his
political rights for life by the No. 2 Intermediate People's Court
of Beijing for embezzling public funds.
</P>
<P>
Traditional, Dotcom Media in Court War Over Infringement
</P>
<P>
Traditional media, mainly newspapers and magazines, angered by
frequent infringement of copyrighted material by dot-coms, are
waging a legal war against their newborn but thriving competitors.
</P>
<P>
"Why do these network media steal others' articles while
spending so heavily on building up their own image?" asked Cheng
Chibing, editor-in-chief of the Life Info magazine, at a news
conference in Beijing Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
