<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0030 GMT, July 15 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- While offering a rather bleak assessment of
the current status of talks on the dispute over Western Sahara, U.
N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan Friday expressed the hope for some
progress at the forthcoming meetings of experts and recommended a
three-month extension of the U.N. mission in Western Sahara.
</P>
<P>
In his latest report on Western Sahara to the Security Council,
Annan said that despite the efforts of his personal envoy, James
Baker III, there had been no progress during the June 28 meeting
in London in resolving any of the multiple problems impending the
implementation of the 1988 settlement plan. (UN-W.Sahara)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PRAGUE -- The Czech Association of Forced Laborers Friday
praised the German parliament for passing a bill earlier in the
day on the compensation of victims of Nazi slave labor during
World War II.
</P>
<P>
"After a year and a half of negotiations with Germany we
finally achieved what we wanted. After 44 years it means not only
financial but also moral compensation," the Czech News Agency
quoted Deputy Chairman of the Association Karel Horak as saying. (
Germany-Nazi-Compensation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA -- The number of people facing food shortage in
Ethiopia has increased to 10.5 million, the country's Disaster
Prevention and Preparedness Commission said Friday.
</P>
<P>
This number was based on the findings of the various study
teams dispatched to assess the drought conditions in all regions
except states of Somali and Afar, according to a statement by the
commission. (Ethiopia-Drought)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- The AIDS pandemic, if not curbed, would cause a
"catastrophe of an unimaginable scale" and bring economies to a
standstill, the World Bank said Friday.
</P>
<P>
"As much as we focus on Africa, which is the global epicenter
of the epidemic, we are equally concerned about the growing
epidemics in Asia and eastern Europe, as well as in Latin America -
-especially the Caribbean," the World Bank said in a paper
presented to the 13th International AIDS Conference in Durban,
South Africa, which ended on Friday. (WB-AIDS)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Argentine President Fernando de la Rua said
Friday that Argentina will not decline its claim of sovereignty
over the Malvinas Islands.
</P>
<P>
De la Rua explained that this does not mean hostility or will
affect the relations of his country with the United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
The Argentine president made this statement one day after the
Foreign Ministry presented a protest to the United Kingdom for "
violation of the Argentine air space."
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministry filed the protest Thursday night after
British aircraft overflew a fleet of Argentine fishing boats that
were operating within its exclusive economic zone and outside the
limits of the Outer Conservation Zone. (Argentina-Malvinas)
</P>
</TEXT>
