<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Review of Top Legal News Events in China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The following are top legal news
events that took place in China last week.
</P>
<P>
Murderers of German Family Sentenced to Death
</P>
<P>
The Intermediate People's Court in Nanjing City, the capital of
east China's Jiangsu Province, Friday granted death penalty to all
four jobless youths who are convicted of murdering and robbing a
German family of four.
</P>
<P>
At midnight on April 1, the four accused, Zhong Weiyang, Liu
Guangyuan, Ding Shanyang, and Zhang Eryang, who are all from
Shuyang County, Jiangsu Province, broke into the Nanjing residence
of the Pfrang family and stabbed to death all the family members
including Jurgen Hermann Pfrang and his wife, Petra Pfrang, and
their two children, daughter Sandra Melanie Pfrang and Thorsten
Oliver Pfrang.
</P>
<P>
 China Cooperates with US in Copyright Protection
</P>
<P>
China is cooperating with the United States in combating
rampant copyright infringement in the country.
</P>
<P>
Xu Chao, deputy director of the Copyright Department of the
State Copyright Bureau, said that China has always been spreading
information on copyright protection among its people, and the
United States can do a lot in this regard.
</P>
<P>
 Beijing to Hold Child Safety, Self-defense Exhibition
</P>
<P>
A Sino-British exhibition focusing on child safety and self-
defense will be held in Beijing from July 15 to 23, aiming at
increasing public awareness of children's rights and helping them
to protect themselves.
</P>
<P>
The event, organized by the British Council and China's People'
s University of Public Security, is also aimed at preventing
children from becoming involved in crime. It centers on the law
and legal rights concerning children, and draws from both British
and Chinese experience.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000715.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Science News: Weekly Highlights (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chinese Students Win Gold Medals at Int'l Chemistry Olympiad
</P>
<P>
Four Chinese middle school students won three gold medals and
one silver at the 32nd International Chemistry Olympiad, according
to sources from the China Association of Science and Technology.
</P>
<P>
A total of 208 students from 54 countries and regions
participated in the contest in Copenhagen, capital of Denmark.
</P>
<P>
Scientists Issue Alarm of Intensified Solar Activity
</P>
<P>
Chinese astronomers who observed on Tuesday the most severe
outbreak of solar activity in four years have issued alarm of
disastrous space weather in the coming 12 days.
</P>
<P>
Yan Yihua, chief scientist with the Beijing Observatory under
the Chinese Academy of Sciences, said they recorded the peak value
of solar activity as massive solar energy was released at 6:13 a.m.
(Beijing Time), which was about 3,000 billion times of the
explosion of atomic bomb over Hiroshima, Japan by the United
States during World War II.
</P>
<P>
China-U.S. Joint Promotion of High-Tech SMEs Discussed
</P>
<P>
Chinese and U.S. government officials, businessmen and
personnel from venture capital organizations gathered in Beijing
on July 12 to probe partnering and investing opportunities for
promotion of high-tech small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs).
</P>
<P>
China is to establish soon a high-tech stock market for high-
tech SMEs, Chinese Vice-Minister of Science and Technology Xu
Guanhua told a symposium jointly sponsored by the Ministry of
Science and Technology and the U.S. Department of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
China Monitors Land Use with Satellite Remote Sensing Tech
</P>
<P>
The land use situation in China's large cities is being
monitored by watchful eyes in the sky.
</P>
<P>
China is employing satellite remote sensing technology to
effectively check the occupation of arable land and help
strengthen the administration of land resources, according to the
Ministry of Land and Resources.
</P>
<P>
International Seminar on Scientific Co-op to Be Held in
Xinjiang
</P>
<P>
The Altay international seminar on scientific and technological
cooperation will be held July 19-21 in northwest China's Xinjiang
Uygur Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The seminar will be jointly organized by the Ministry of
Science and Technology and the government of Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
 High-Tech Enterprises Urged to Get Listed
</P>
<P>
China will speed up experiment with venture investment and get
more high-tech businesses listed, said Xu Guanhua, vice-minister
of Science and Technology on July 5.
</P>
<P>
"Along with economic globalization and China's accession into
the World Trade Organization, the country is facing both
opportunities and challenges to develop its high-tech industry, "
said Xu while attending a forum on industry of high and new
technologies and capital market in China held in Wuhan, capital of
Hubei Province.  
</P>
</TEXT>
