<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2100GMT, Saturday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- The decade-old U.N. sanctions against Iraq claimed
lives of more than 8,000 Iraqis in June, bringing the total number
of victims to 1,324,760 since 1990, the Iraqi Health Ministry
announced Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said in a statement that 5,511 children under the
age of five died of diarrhea, pneumonia, respiratory infections and
malnutrition last month.
</P>
<P>
And 2,671 elderly people died of heart diseases, hypertension,
diabetes and malignant neoplasms. (Iraq-Mortality)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran on Saturday successfully test-fired an upgraded
Shahab-3 missile, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The missile, with a range of about 1,280 kilometers, was test-
fired to ensure its conformity with the latest technological
standards, an informed source at the Defense Ministry was quoted
assaying.
</P>
<P>
According to the source, this was the second time that the
Shahab-3 missile had been tested. (Iran-Missile-Test)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Two reformist lawyers, Mohsen Rahami and Shirin Ebadi,
went on trial at Branch 16 of Tehran's public court on Saturday,
the Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The two lawyers, arrested last month, have been accused by the
conservative judiciary of involvement in duplicating and
distributing a videocassette that included "insulting" remarks on
some ranking officials.
</P>
<P>
A source in Tehran's justice department said the trial was held
in camera because of "some documents related to the case that
involve the national security." (Iran-Lawyers-Trial)
</P>
