<HEADLINE> Mortar Blasts Hit Northern Tehran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Several mortar shells exploded
Saturday night in northern Tehran, causing damage to some
residential units, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The shells hit a residential area at 2135 hours local time (1705
GMT) close to the state Mint House near the crossroad of Shahid
Hemat highway and Niavaran highway, eyewitnesses were quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Parts of the headquarters of the Iranian elite Islamic
Revolutionary Guards Corps are located several kilometers north of
the explosion area.
</P>
<P>
It is not clear so far whether the explosions caused any
casualties and no one has claimed responsibility for the mortar
attack.
</P>
<P>
Iran's main opposition group Mujahedeen Khalq Organization (MKO)
has launched several mortar attacks on government and military
targets in the Iranian capital of Tehran during the past six
months.
</P>
<P>
The MKO, a major political and military group which had fought
against the Iranian shah regime before the 1979 Islamic revolution,
was outlawed in 1981 and fled into Iraq following sharp differences
with the then Iranian government.
</P>
<P>
Labeled by Iran a "terrorist group," the MKO has launched a
series of cross-border attacks on Iran in recent years, including
assassinating senior Iranian officials. In retaliation, Iranian
armed forces also launched several air raids on the MKO bases in
Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
