<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba Starts AIDS Prevention Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Cuba has started a program to tell
young people how to protect themselves from AIDS, as part of the
efforts to reduce the incidence of this disease in the country,
the local press reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The new education project titled "Summer 2000 Campaign" aims at
informing the youths through television and posters about the
several ways to protect themselves from the Acquired Immuno-
Deficiency Syndrome (AIDS).
</P>
<P>
The health authorities said that July and August, the vacation
months for Cuban students, are the time when young people take
part in more recreational activities that can lead to unsafe sex
relations.
</P>
<P>
The implementation of the new program concurs with the 13th
World Conference on AIDS in Durban, South Africa, at which
scientists and technicians join their efforts to establish a joint
action against the disease caused by the Human Immuno-Defficiency
Virus (HIV).
</P>
<P>
Studies carried out in the island revealed that there are many
young people who think that they cannot be reached by the deadly
disease, and have a very low perception of the risk.
</P>
<P>
Cuban Public Health Minister Carlos Dotres said that 2,762 HIV
positive cases have been detected since 1986, of which 1,036 were
developed into AIDS, and 720 people died.
</P>
<P>
Local estimates for the year 2010 raised the figure of HIV
positive people to 7,500, of whom 60 percent are concentrated in
the capital, and that this is an incentive to continue the fight
against the disease.
</P>
<P>
The first cases of AIDS patients appeared in Cuba in the 1980s,
and since then a campaign has started, first to control, and then
to reduce the incidence of the disease 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
