<HEADLINE> U.S. Sanctions To Damage Peru's Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Peruvian exports would lose custom
tariff benefits this year for 80 million dollars if the United
States unilaterally applies trade sanctions to this country,
economic analyst Javier Mujica said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The specialist said that some 80 percent of Peruvian exports to
the U.S. market could be affected by the cancellation of the
tariff privileges.
</P>
<P>
Peruvian exports to the United States amount to more than 700
million dollars a year and basically they are textiles,
handicrafts, minerals and agricultural and livestock commodities.
</P>
<P>
Mujica said that the exclusion from the U.S. Generalized System
of Tariff Preferences (SPG) was already threatened in 1994, when U.
S. labor unions denounced the illegal subsidies of Peruvian
exports as a consequence of Peruvian labor laws of 1992.
</P>
<P>
At that time the government of President Alberto Fujimori
promised the United States to coordinate the labor legislation of
his country with the international standards and in this way he
prevented Peru from being excluded from the SPG
</P>
<P>
Mujica said that the sanctions that restrict trade and
investments are not, for their very nature, among the first
unilateral measures implemented by the U.S. international policies.
</P>
<P>
The analyst added that the United States will implement
unilateral measures when it understands that other nations are not
fully convinced that they must do it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
