<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief Warns Sierra Leonean Rebels Not to Oppose Rescue Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 15 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan Saturday warned Sierra Leonean rebels not to oppose the
operation launched by the U.N. mission to rescue peacekeepers who
had been trapped by them since May this year.
</P>
<P>
More than 220 U.N. peacekeepers trapped in eastern Sierra
Leone broke out from their positions with the help of fellow
peacekeepers from the United Nations Mission in Sierra Leone (
UNAMSIL) Saturday morning and began fighting their way towards
safety.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued by his spokesman's office, Annan warned
the rebel Revolutionary United Front (RUF) that it was in their
interest not to oppose this legitimate effort and hoped that
further violence can be avoided.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief stressed that the extraction operation was
aimed at ensuring the security of United Nations personnel and
restoring their freedom of movement.
</P>
<P>
"This morning, UNAMSIL lunched a military operation to extract
the 233 peacekeepers, who had been surrounded by the RUF at their
compound in Kailahun. The secretary-general is gratified that 40
of them have now been brought to safety and that the UNAMSIL
operation to bring the remaining 193 back to safe ground has made
good progress," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"However, the United Nations forces have yet to cover some
distance in a difficult area controlled by hostile rebels before
reaching the nearest United Nations base at Daru," the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
"The use of force by UNAMSIL to extract its personnel from the
area has become inevitable. Indeed, for over two months, the RUF
maintained its illegal encirclement of the United Nations
peacekeepers at Kailahun and had prevented them from exercising
their freedom of movement, which is a fundamental principle in all
United Nations peacekeeping operations," the statement noted.
</P>
<P>
"Throughout this period, intensive diplomatic and political
efforts, at all levels, to ensure their security and restore their
freedom of movement by peaceful means were unsuccessful. Moreover,
the resupply of the surrounded peacekeepers has recently been
severely curtailed as a result of the increasingly threatening
posture adopted by the RUF and the deteriorating road conditions
in the area," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
The peacekeepers were sent to Sierra Leone to monitor a peace
agreement and disarmament that was to have ended a civil war that
began in 1991.
</P>
<P>
But the RUF refused to disarm and took U.N. peacekeepers
hostage when they ventured to diamond-mining areas they control.
</P>
</TEXT>
