<HEADLINE> Alitalia Aims to Forge New Alliance With Foreign Airlines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Alitalia, the Italian national
airline, plans to forge new alliances and rebuild its fleet to
reverse its current dismal trend which this year saw the first
semester balance push profits into negative ground, CEO Domenico
Cempella told union leaders here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Cempella said the first semester losses were due to a
combination of factors, including the broken accord with KLM Royal
Dutch Airlines and the sharp rise in oil prices which alone drove
operating costs up 150 million euros.
</P>
<P>
According to Cempella, the KLM break cost Alitalia more than
100 million euros and damaged the airline both because it
dramatically reduced the number of passengers and because of the
costs incurred in covering routes which previously had been
covered by the alliance.
</P>
<P>
Cempella also said that rising oil prices are making it more
and more difficult for smaller airlines to keep their heads above
water in a fiercely competitive market.
</P>
<P>
He added that Alitalia risks serving only a niche market or
becoming a secondary player if it cannot manage to find a new
partner and build up its fleet, especially of larger planes used
for intercontinental flights.
</P>
<P>
Alitalia has been dogged by problems since 1999, due largely to
the numerous delays in developing Milan's new Malpensa airport
into a fully operational international hub, a major factor leading
to the KLM break.
</P>
<P>
Although Alitalia openly announced its intention to search for
a new partner virtually the minute it was unceremoniously dumped
by KLM in April, so far no sure candidate has been announced.
</P>
<P>
Today, the CEO avoided reiterating the claim he made last month
that by the end of 2000 Alitalia profits would reach the 1999
levels, which that year registered consolidated net profits of 6
million euros, already a sharp fall from the previous year's 200
million profit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
