<HEADLINE> Cubans Demand End to U.S. Cuban Adjustment Act </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Some 20,000 Cuban demonstrators
demanded Saturday the derogation by the United States of a law
that grants automatic asylum to Cubans who abandon the island.
</P>
<P>
Revolutionary Armed Forces Minister and No. 2 leader in Cuba
Raul Castro attended the rally held in La Maquina, 900 kilometers
east of Havana.
</P>
<P>
"Down with the Cuban Adjustment Act" and "Down with the
blockade" were some of the slogans shouted by the demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
The Cuban authorities said that the Cuban Adjustment Act
promulgated by the U.S. government encourages Cubans to emigrate
illegally to U.S. territory.
</P>
<P>
Under the 1994 and 1995 immigration accords, 20,000 Cubans are
allowed to immigrate to the United States legally.
</P>
<P>
In line with those accords, Cubans trying to enter the United
States illegally who are intercepted at sea must be returned to
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
But unlike other illegal immigrants, Cubans who manage to evade
the Coast Guard and reach U.S. shores are allowed to seek legal
residency and work permits under the so-called Cuban Adjustment
Act. 
</P>
</TEXT>
