<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- A delegation of three United States
senators is visiting Havana Saturday to know first hand the
interest of the Cuban government in the normalization of relations
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The three legislators who arrived Friday are led by Max Baucus,
a Democrat for the state of Montana, and is made up of Daniel
Akaka, a Democrat from Hawaii, and Pat Roberts, a Republican of
Kansas.
</P>
<P>
Baucus was one of the sponsors in May of a bill of law aimed at
derogating the U.S. laws that affect the relations with the island.
</P>
<P>
The visitors expect to hold talks during their brief visit with
senior Cuban government officials, and they will offer a press
conference Sunday afternoon, a little before their return to their
country.
</P>
<P>
The visit occurs two months after two Democrat congressmen for
the state of Kansas, Senator Blanche Lincoln, and representative
Marion Berry, explored the possibility of business in the island,
together with a delegation of rice producers from that country.
</P>
<P>
Several delegations from different levels of the U.S. society
have toured the island this year and have stated their support for
the establishment of normal links between the two nations.
</P>
<P>
After the return to Cuba on June 28 of boy Elian Ginzalez, who
was the bone of contention between Washington and Havana, the
government presided over by Fidel Castro has centered its efforts
in ending the trade embargo and the derogation of other anti-Cuba
laws imposed by the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
