<HEADLINE> Students Conflict Worsens Dominican Republic Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The social situation in the
Dominican Republic worsened Saturday with the paralyzation of the
Santo Domingo Autonomous University by orders of the authorities.
</P>
<P>
Rector Miguel Rosado suspended faculty and administrative
activities for 48 hours, after disgruntled students occupied the
campus of the institution, according to reports reaching here from
Santo Domingo, the Dominican Republic's capital.
</P>
<P>
The Dominican Students Federation (FED) demonstrators protested
the increase by a little more than 1.50 dollars the registration
fee for the summer course offered every year by that university.
</P>
<P>
Rosado said that the students' demand is illogical because the
increase of the registration fee to reduce in part the budget
deficit of the university is far below the real cost of the course,
estimated at five dollars.
</P>
<P>
The FED leadership warned that they will continue to occupy the
areas until the rector discusses with the organization the fee
increase established by the university council, while the council
announced that it is studying sanctions to be applied to those
students.
</P>
<P>
The dispute in the university occurs in the middle of political
confrontations between the transition commissions formed by the
Dominican Revolutionary Party (PRD) and the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
